---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import LogIsRuntimeKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/LogIsRuntimeKeystone.astro";
import EventProduceConsumeFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/EventProduceConsumeFlow.astro";
import ReplayLayersFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ReplayLayersFlow.astro";
import IdentityLayersFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/IdentityLayersFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="01" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      Without a replayable fact ledger there is no debuggable, projectable, or evolvable Agent. This
      chapter establishes the Runtime Event Log as the canonical source, and why Session / UI /
      Provider contexts can only be projections.
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§01 · Scene"
    title="Start from a deceptively simple request"
    lede="An Agent is not “how to call an LLM once”; it is how an open loop becomes replayable history."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user says: find the failing tests, fix them, and run again. A chat app only needs
      “send to model → wait → display.” A real Agent must read the project, call tools, wait on
      authorization, handle failure/timeouts, feed results back, loop for many rounds, and terminate
      cleanly as completed / failed / aborted.
    </p>
    <p>
      The UI needs live updates; the next model call needs trustworthy history; a crash must not leave
      the system stuck “running”; after the user hits stop, late provider events must not rewrite the
      outcome to “completed.”
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Runtime’s real job: turn an open loop of streaming output, tool side effects, human
      intervention, and process failure into a fact history that can be re-interpreted and replayed.
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§01 · Keystone"
    title="State is not a table — it is a function of the log"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; NewsLiquid tokens and hand keystones stay fixed."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Runtime Events Log at the center; Model History / UI / Terminal / Recovery are projections — never write-back truth."
      alt="Centered Runtime Events Log with four projections: Model History, UI Read Model, Terminal Fact, Recovery/Compact; invariant: Log is source of truth; state is a materialized view."
    >
      <LogIsRuntimeKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Maka’s core judgment is not which model SDK it picked:
      <strong
        >the Event Log stores facts; Session, Run, UI, model context, and recovery are consumers or
        projections of that log.</strong
      >
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="State as projection">State(t) = Project(RuntimeEvents[0..t], policy, runtime configuration)</pre>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="spine"
    label="§01 · Spine"
    title="Produce, append, project, consume"
    lede="The same log can be interpreted into many states — no consumer may rewrite the truth."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Produce → Durable append → Project → Consume; the UI transcript is always a consumer."
      alt="Four-step pipeline: Produce facts, Durable append, Project, Consume views."
    >
      <EventProduceConsumeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Model History Projector → messages for the next model call</li>
      <li>Runtime Read Model → dialogue, tool activity, and Turn state for the UI</li>
      <li>Terminal Fact Classifier → final outcome of a Run</li>
      <li>Recovery → which facts were durable before process exit</li>
      <li>Context / Compaction → a smaller working context that keeps key semantics (see §03)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This is not a normal application log that describes “what the code did” after the fact. A
      RuntimeEvent <em>is</em> business semantics. Delete the log and the system loses any reliable
      basis to rebuild interaction state.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside</p>
      <p>
        Runtime Event Log architecture chapter land:
        <a href="/history/pr/768">maka:pr:768</a>
        (docs: add Runtime Event Log architecture chapter).
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="event"
    label="§01 · Event"
    title="What one RuntimeEvent must hold"
    lede="Not role + text — orthogonal facts that can be projected, paired, and terminated."
  >
    <p>A fact should answer at least these orthogonal dimensions:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Identity</strong> — session / invocation / run / turn / branch</li>
      <li><strong>Ordering</strong> — id, timestamp, and ledger order</li>
      <li><strong>Source</strong> — role, author</li>
      <li><strong>Content</strong> — text, thinking, function call/response, error</li>
      <li><strong>Actions</strong> — state delta, permission, artifact, usage, end invocation</li>
      <li><strong>Correlation</strong> — tool call, provider event, step, and artifact refs</li>
      <li><strong>Lifecycle</strong> — partial stream fragments vs durable facts vs terminal facts</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Model history therefore need not be reverse-parsed from a UI transcript; the UI is not the
      source of truth. Projectors select non-partial, model-visible events from RuntimeEvents, then
      materialize by provider capability.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="replay"
    label="§01 · Replay"
    title="Three meanings of “replay the state space”"
    lede="Current ships semantic replay; do not smuggle wire-level determinism in as a delivered promise."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Semantic replay (Current) ≠ Provider-native (capability-gated) ≠ Bit-exact wire (Target)."
      alt="Three columns: Semantic replay, Provider-native, Bit-exact wire."
    >
      <ReplayLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ol class="plain-list plain-list--ol">
      <li>
        <strong>Semantic replay (Current)</strong> — given the ledger, rebuild text, thinking, tool
        pairing, permissions, usage, and terminal facts; next-turn model history and completed
        Session read models prefer this construction.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Provider-native replay (capability-gated)</strong> — providers differ on tool history
        / signed thinking; plan first, then choose native, text-only, or explicit degrade. Replayable
        ≠ dumping JSONL into an arbitrary model.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bit-exact wire replay (Target / not claimed)</strong> — today’s Event Log stores
        canonical message semantics, not a full snapshot of every HTTP byte. System prompt, tool
        schema, options, and projection policy still participate in request generation. Bit-exact
        would need separate versioning of config and request shape.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Teaching centers Current semantic replay. Target directions are labeled explicitly so wishes
        are not written as shipped facts — matching Maka architecture-doc discipline.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="ids"
    label="§01 · Identity"
    title="Four identities that must not collapse"
    lede="A Turn is not a Run; a chat message is not execution state."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Session / Turn / Run / Invocation stay distinct so retries need not rewrite the event protocol."
      alt="Four columns: Session, Turn, Run, Invocation."
    >
      <IdentityLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Session</strong> — long-lived interaction ownership (sessionId)</li>
      <li><strong>Turn</strong> — one user-visible Q&amp;A round (turnId)</li>
      <li><strong>Run</strong> — one durable execution attempt (runId / AgentRun)</li>
      <li><strong>Invocation</strong> — one Runner-spec call boundary (invocationId)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      On the default path runId and invocationId often coincide, but they should stay distinct
      conceptually: future retries and multi-attempt flows should not rewrite the whole event
      protocol. Without an execution envelope the system only sees “some messages appeared,” and
      cannot reliably answer whether this execution truly ended.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="invariant"
    label="§01 · Invariant"
    title="Boundaries that must hold"
    lede="Log is the source of truth; state is a materialized view."
  >
    <p>
      Two rough lineages: ADK-style “Session history is fact; working context is projection,” and
      the distributed-systems intuition of log-first / event sourcing — do not treat every downstream
      view as an independent truth.
    </p>
    <p>
      That yields a terminal invariant shared by later chapters:
      <strong
        >a Run header cannot declare completion by itself; it must be backed by a terminal
        RuntimeEvent.</strong
      >
      §02 builds the Tool Result evidence layer on this; §03 shows how Compaction changes projections
      without mutating facts.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Present: keystone + produce/consume flow + three replay layers</li>
      <li>
        Aside: <a href="/history/pr/768">maka:pr:768</a>
      </li>
      <li>Still open: more volume figures, a11y pass — do not mark checklist complete</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

